Reading plans with explain.

The explain method exposes the plans that Catalyst built, and it is the single best way to see why a query is slow. There are five modes, each a different lens on the same query.

Simple mode is the default. It shows just the physical plan.

Extended mode shows all four plans — parsed, analyzed, optimized, and physical.

Codegen mode shows the generated java virtual machine code, per stage.

Cost mode shows the optimized plan, annotated with row-count estimates for each node.

And formatted mode shows the physical plan, plus a separate operator-details section.

Now, the real skill is reading the physical plan, and you read it bottom-up. The scan is at the bottom, and data flows upward through each operator.

Two things to look for. An exchange node marks a shuffle, and a shuffle is a stage boundary. And a whole-stage-codegen wrapper marks the operators that Tungsten fused together into a single loop.
